<h1 style="margin-top: 20px">Tree Data Structure</h1>

<p style="margin-top:10px; font-size:20px;">
    Tree data structures are sorted collections of data that allow for efficient search and inserting algorithms to be implemented. Trees consist of nodes, connected by edges which all
    eventually link back the root node as you can see in the figure below. Each node may contain one or more data 'items', and each node may connect to zero, one or several other nodes. If a node 'a'
    is connected to another node 'b' directly below it, node 'a' would be considered the parent of it's child node 'b'. If a third node 'c' were to be connected to 'a' as well, nodes 'b' and 'c'
    would be considered siblings. A subtree is created each time a new node is added, for example, when L,E,F and G were added this created a subtree as shown in the figure. Or take
    for example, when H was added, it created a leaf node which by definition is a subtree consisting of exactly one node.
    By this definition a tree is a recursive data strucutre because each node is the root of a smaller subtree.
</p>

